gods, and that therefore, perhaps Jove made that Water their obliging Oath. Ariſtotle, M • taphyſ. l. 1. c. 3. conceiveth, that the Poets by this fiction, intended to ſignifie, that water is the original of all things. So Thales Mileſius ſaid, that, water is initium rerum; Deum autem, eam Meutem quae, ex aqua cuncta fingeret, as Cicero ſaith, De nat. Deox. lib. 1. according to that of Moſes, Gen. 1. 2. So the god's Oath ſeemeth to have been by the firſt beginning of things. Other reaſons may be ſeen in Cal. R • odiginus, lib. 27. c. 5. Of this opinion, Plutarch ſheweth Homer to be, lib. De Homero, where he citeth Thales for it; and, after them, Xenophanes. The reaſons of whoſe conjecture, Euſebius giveth, De praepar. Evang. lib. 14. c. 14. Servius in Aen. 6. ſaith, Acheron hath its name, qua ••
